			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"><span style="text-decoration: underline">No more Oshur:</span>  Didn't like it, so good riddance.  Still trying out the Battle Islands, but kinda like them so far.  It'll be interesting to see what role they play in strategy once the novelty wears off.  Fewer bases each means they should be more susceptible to blitz attacks.  Although they have a reputation for turning into stalemates, I think that's partly because they're getting an awful lot of action from casual players who may be more likely to foot-zerg en masse, which I suspect is not exactly the most dynamic style of battle.  I'm particularly keen on seeing how single-base Nexus can possibly be defended -- mass a raid force, push empire-lock through the warpgate, base succumbs in the blink of an eye to massive population advantage, and the pressure's on the enemy to prove they can resecure within 15 minutes versus your Red Alert force.  If they manage to do so, and the attack fails, just leave and try again later; it should pop to this type of attack sooner or later... right?
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">New global map:</span>  I hate it.  Guess I'm not the only one.  Hopefully SOE makes it more user-friendly.
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">New lattice system:</span>  Interesting; not really sure what to make of it yet.  At a glance:
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">1.</span> Standardized three-warpgate system on each non-home continent, err planet, often lending itself towards each empire having lattice from one warpgate.  I don't know how I feel about this; it seems like often the attacking team is going to be stuck with only a single link to a planet they're attacking as opposed to often having two under the old lattice system.  This one-warpgate attack should be easier to counter as long as enough defenders are massed before that first base gets captured.  On the other hand, the spectre of three-team battles should be around more often.  Is the game going to become even more defensively-oriented due to attackers (normally) having only one link, or will empires emphasize attack timing in such a way to be the backhacking third empire and hopefully make easy gains?
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">2.</span> Searhus, the "half TR, half VS" planet (although its third link should be, as usual, normally controlled by the third empire) appears very unappealing to attack from the TR point of view.  Guess which attack route the TR normally get when attacking?  Good old Iva!  Not only do you have to start with a lousy Bio Lab, but you have to follow it up with an LLU run from the northwest that goes right past their zerg camped out on the western fields.  Tech is also three bases deep, adding insult to injury.  This has got to be one of the worst continental starts in the game, it belongs to the TR.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">3.</span> If we assume each empire tries to lay claim to a "sub-home planet" (TR-Hossin, NC-Cyssor, VS-Amerish), the number of bases in the two-planet combination of "home + sub-home" is lowest for the TR, which I assume in itself can't be a good thing for daily win totals.  (TR-21 bases, NC-26 bases, VS-24 bases)
<br />

<br />
One could argue that a partial counter to this is that the combined number of bases in the two other places that the TR home planet link to (and are therefore likely to attack) is high, since Esamir and Searhus both sport a bunch.  But then I'd say that, as talked about before, the Forseral link to Searhus is a very weak one from a strategic point of view, so that's potentially kind of nullified.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">4.</span> Strategy!  At a glance, the very basic global strategies that come to my mind are:
<br />

<br />
4a. Generic empire strategy:  Establish your home planet.  Capture the three planets that your home planet links to.  Now you have 4 out of the 10 planets (if you consider the Battle Islands collectively as equal to a planet in terms of the number of bases), so just play a lot of defense and you'll normally be the daily winner.
<br />

<br />
4b. TR-specific strategy:  Secure Forseral.  If Searhus isn't red, then let it be, since it's going to be a pain to get back.  Capture Hossin and Esamir as usual.  Go for the Battle Islands next.  Now Ishundar suggests itself, since the TR now have two links there.  (Capturing five planets, haha, is that optimistic enough for you guys?)
<br />

<br />
4c. Just camp what you have and be opportunistic with backhacks.  Dunno what else I can say about this one.
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
I'm done rambling now, so here's wishing GeeGee's to all.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
